# 🐧 Linux File System Structure

## 📌 Overview
Linux follows a hierarchical directory structure where `/` is the root of everything.

---

## 📂 Important Directories

### 📁 Core System

- `/` → Root directory (base of entire file system)

- `/bin` → Basic commands (for all users)  
  _Ex: ls, cp, mv_

- `/sbin` → System/admin commands (superuser)  
  _Ex: fdisk, reboot_

- `/boot` → Boot loader files (kernel, GRUB)

- `/dev` → Device files  
  _Ex: /dev/sda, /dev/null_

- `/lib`, `/lib64` → System libraries required by binaries  

---

### ⚙️ Configuration & System

- `/etc` → Configuration files  
  _Ex: /etc/passwd, /etc/nginx/nginx.conf_

- `/proc` → Process & system info (virtual filesystem)  
  _Ex: /proc/cpuinfo_

- `/sys` → Kernel & hardware info  

- `/run` → Runtime data (temporary system info)

---

### 👤 User & Data

- `/home` → Home directory for users  
  _Ex: /home/sahil_

- `/root` → Home directory for root user  

- `/usr` → User programs & application data  
  _Ex: /usr/bin, /usr/lib_

---

### 💾 Storage & Mounting

- `/media` → Auto-mounted external devices (USB, CD)  

- `/mnt` → Temporary mount point  

---

### 📦 Software & Services

- `/opt` → Third-party software installation  

- `/srv` → Service-related data (web, ftp)

---

### 📊 Logs & Temp

- `/var` → Variable data (logs, cache)  
  _Ex: /var/log_

- `/tmp` → Temporary files (auto deleted)

---

## 🔥 Key Points (Interview Ready)

- `/etc` → configs  
- `/var/log` → logs  
- `/home` → user data  
- `/bin` vs `/sbin` → user vs admin commands  
- `/usr` → applications  
- `/tmp` → temporary files  

---

## 🎯 One-Line Summary

👉  
**“Linux file system is hierarchical, starting from `/`, where each directory has a specific purpose like configuration, logs, user data, and system binaries.”**
